==English==

===Etymology===
Latin ''[[urgere]]''.  Cognate with Old English [[wrecan]] (English ''[[wreak]]'').

===Pronunciation===
*:Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ɜː(r)dʒ|-ɜː(r)dʒ]]

===Noun===
'''urge'''  (''plural:'' '''[[urges]]''')

# A strong [[desire]]; an [[itch]] to do something.

====Translations====
*Finnish: [[halu]]
*German: [[Drang]] {{m}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|urg|ing}}

# ''[[transitive]]:'' To press; to [[push]]; to drive; to [[impel]]; to force [[onward]].
# ''[[transitive]]:'' To press the mind or will of; to [[ply]] with motives, [[argument]]s, [[persuade|persuasion]], or [[importunity]].
# ''[[transitive]]:'' To [[provoke]]; to [[exasperate]].
# ''[[transitive]]:'' To present in an urgent manner; to [[insist]] upon.
# ''[[transitive]],'' {{obsolete}}: To treat with forcible means; to take severe or violent measures with; as, to urge an ore with intense heat.
# ''[[intransitive]]:'' To press onward or forward.
# ''[[intransitive]]:'' To be pressing in argument; to insist; to persist.

